    {
        "content": "<p>With the much-maligned autoImplicit feature on by default, you either have to poke around quite a bit or do what you did, which is ask someone else what's wrong. It's possible to turn the autoimplicit feature off globally in all of your projects (and I would recommend it): <a href=\"https://proofassistants.stackexchange.com/questions/2189/project-wide-set-option-autoimplicit-false-in-lean-4\">https://proofassistants.stackexchange.com/questions/2189/project-wide-set-option-autoimplicit-false-in-lean-4</a></p>",
        "id": 476538788,
        "sender_full_name": "Chris Bailey",
        "timestamp": 1728753322
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>what does this feature do?</p>",
        "id": 476557125,
        "sender_full_name": "Paul Crowley",
        "timestamp": 1728772361
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>So far I have been able to do all my examples with just one <code>import Mathlib.Tactic</code> which seems to pull in much of the common definitions and tactics.</p>\n<p>It seems to work for your example too.</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Lean4\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"kn\">import</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Mathlib</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">Tactic</span>\n\n<span class=\"kn\">theorem</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">exists_add_of_lt</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">{</span><span class=\"n\">a</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">b</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">ℕ</span><span class=\"o\">}</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">h</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">a</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">&lt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">b</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">∃</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">c</span><span class=\"o\">,</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">a</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">+</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">c</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">b</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"k\">by</span>\n<span class=\"w\">  </span><span class=\"n\">use</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">b</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">-</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">a</span>\n<span class=\"w\">  </span><span class=\"n\">rw</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">[</span><span class=\"n\">Nat</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">add_sub_of_le</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">h</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">le</span><span class=\"o\">]</span>\n</code></pre></div>",
        "id": 476557500,
        "sender_full_name": "rzeta0",
        "timestamp": 1728772885
    },
    {
        "content": "<blockquote>\n<p>what does this feature do?</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>When on (as it is by default), undefined variables will be converted into implicit parameters instead of giving you an error. So in your example, Lean didn't know what \\N was, so it converted it into a parameter. And then you got an error later, because &lt; is not defined for arbitrary types.</p>",
        "id": 476560039,
        "sender_full_name": "Niels Voss",
        "timestamp": 1728776010
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"764789\">Paul Crowley</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/113489-new-members/topic/What.20do.20I.20need.20to.20import.20to.20do.20basic.20natural.20number.20stuff.3F/near/476534727\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>This works, thanks! How should I have found this out for myself?</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>I searched <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/\">Mathlib4 docs</a> for the notation <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/Mathlib/Data/Nat/Notation.html#term%E2%84%95\"><code>ℕ</code></a> and the <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/Mathlib/Tactic/Use.html\"><code>use</code></a> tactic. I admit it's a bit tricky.</p>",
